League of Legends teams, players, and analysts have moved from an emphasis on stylish 1v1 outplays to strategic objective control. Although these outplays are still celebrated across the game, strong game management and objective control ultimately lead to victories. Objectives like dragons and barons are often cited as deciders of wins and losses. This makes sense: these late-game objectives provide a major damage boost. As such, the winner (IG), a semifinalist, and a quarterfinalist made the top 5 in average dragons per game.

Notably, Team Liquid and Phong Vu Buffalo, did not place well but still maintained a high number of dragons. As such, we note that there may be different factors that are more important to game wins. Although dragons and objectives are important in helping teams gain these boosts, ultimately it is teamfights that lead to the result of a game. Gold is critical in purchasing items to win those fights.

Gold matters more earlier in the game during that time, a larger gold difference presents a more drastic item difference. A greater difference in gold allows one team to dominate the other in teamfights. Gold difference also helps normalize the data, as some games may result in more actions and thus result in more overall gold. As such, we note that the winner (IG), 2nd place (Fnatic), and two quarterfinalists maintained the strongest gold difference at 10 minutes. Room for error still remains: Team Liquid placed only slightly better than the median.

The trend of success with positive gold difference continues with the teams that did poorly. 4 of the 5 teams depicted performed below average. The only outlier, Edward Gaming, placed as a quarterfinalist.

Although these trends are not absolute and can only suggest a correlation, we can tell that gold is critical to these teams. As such, we dive deeper into the importance of gold.

The Importance of Gold

High gold generation is often the key to victory. During the games, announcers often show graphs of gold for the two teams. As previously mentioned, teams that generated the most gold ended up placing the highest. Gold is essential to purchasing items - understandably, theres a strong positive correlation between gold earned and gold spent.

Although we have seen that teams that generated the most gold placed well in the tournament, we have not put this conclusion to the test. As both the result of the games and damage output of each champion are extremely important, we want to see how gold impacts damage per minute of a game.

Notably, damage needs to be clarified some players in the game are in supporting roles, and do not focus on damage output. As such, we color by the position to emphasize the players that focus on gold generation (ADC (attack damage carry), Jungle, and Middle), and see a strong positive correlation of damage per minute to total gold.

Given this high correlation, we can use a model to see which objectives affect gold generation the most, and thus can advise teams on which goals to focus on. We then can finally confirm that greater gold differential and total gold generated are correlated with greater chances of victory. Notably, we confirm that gold difference creates a stronger relationship.

Impacting gold generation

Gold is affected by a range of monsters, minions, champions, and towers. Each kill or takedown generates gold - its value is often scaled by importance and difficulty. For example, there are two types of minions, which make up a vast majority of gold generated in the game, are split into 4 types, with values that are highly dependent on their attack range, health, and attack damage. Thus, determining how gold is generated is critical.

In the following graphs, we emphasize this important fact: the position of the player is critical to the amount of gold generated. As such, we highly recommend first coloring by position.
